### Object Methods

When a function is stored as an object property, it is called a **method**.

---

### Adding Methods

```js
let person = {
  name: "John",
  greet: function() {
    console.log("Hello!");
  }
};

person.greet(); // "Hello!"
```

### Shorthand Syntax (ES6)

```js
let person = {
  name: "John",
  greet() {        // No need for : function
    console.log("Hello!");
  }
};
```

---

### Using `this` in Methods

The `this` keyword refers to the **object** that owns the method:

```js
let person = {
  name: "John",
  greet() {
    console.log(`Hello, I am ${this.name}`);
  }
};

person.greet(); // "Hello, I am John"
```

---

### Built-in Object Methods

| Method | Description | Example |
|--------|-------------|---------|
| `Object.keys(obj)` | Returns array of keys | `Object.keys(person)` |
| `Object.values(obj)` | Returns array of values | `Object.values(person)` |
| `Object.entries(obj)` | Returns array of [key, value] | `Object.entries(person)` |
| `Object.assign(target, src)` | Copies properties | `Object.assign({}, obj)` |
| `Object.freeze(obj)` | Makes object immutable | `Object.freeze(obj)` |

---

> **Arrow Functions as Methods:** Avoid using arrow functions as methods -- they do not have their own `this`.

codeExample:
let person = {
  name: "Ibrahim",
  greet() {
    return `Hi, I'm ${this.name}`;
  }
};

console.log(person.greet());
